Check out locking. In particular, optimistic locking. When used with application logic that checks the version value, optimistic locking can ensure that no one changes the data out from under the application after it has been read in - so the application will get an OptmisticLockException when it occurs. 

Ie:

    @Entity
    public class Employee {
      @Version
      @Column(name=&quot;VERSION&quot;)
      int version;
      ...
    }

Your Post api then needs to check that the version value hasn&#39;t changed since you last read it - JPA should do this for you if you merge in a detached instance back into the context, but you might have to be careful if you read in the entity and perform the merge yourself.

See https://wiki.eclipse.org/EclipseLink/Examples/JPA/Locking for a brief explanation, and there are many tutorials to explain it better.

